---
description: This file provides guidelines for writing effective, maintainable tests using TUnit and FakeItEasy.
globs: *.cs, *.Tests.csproj
---
Role Definition:
 - Test Engineer
 - Quality Assurance Specialist
 - CI/CD Expert

General:
  Description: >
    Tests should be reliable, maintainable, and provide meaningful coverage.
    Use TUnit as the primary testing framework and FakeItEasy for mocking, with proper isolation and
    clear patterns for test organization and execution.
  Requirements:
    - Use TUnit as the testing framework
    - Use FakeItEasy for creating fakes/mocks
    - Ensure test isolation
    - Follow consistent patterns
    - Maintain high code coverage
    - Configure proper CI/CD test execution

Project Setup:
  - Configure test projects:
      ```xml
      <Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
        <PropertyGroup>
          <IsPackable>false</IsPackable>
        </PropertyGroup>
        
        <ItemGroup>
          <PackageReference Include="TUnit" />
          <PackageReference Include="FakeItEasy" />
        </ItemGroup>
      </Project>
      ```
    - Note: TUnit includes built-in code coverage support via `--coverage` flag. Do NOT use coverlet.collector or Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk as they are incompatible with TUnit.

Test Class Structure:
  - TUnit automatically provides global usings for common namespaces, so no explicit using statements needed for:
    - `TUnit.Core` (for `[Test]` attribute)
    - `TUnit.Assertions` (for `Assert.That()`)
  - Simple test class structure:
      ```csharp
      public class OrderProcessingTests
      {
          [Test]
          public async Task ProcessOrder_ValidOrder_Succeeds()
          {
              // Test implementation
          }
      }
      ```
  - Use fixtures for shared state:
      ```csharp
      public class DatabaseFixture : IAsyncLifetime
      {
          public DbConnection Connection { get; private set; }
          
          public async Task InitializeAsync()
          {
              Connection = new SqlConnection("connection-string");
              await Connection.OpenAsync();
          }
          
          public async Task DisposeAsync()
          {
              await Connection.DisposeAsync();
          }
      }
      
      public class OrderTests
      {
          private readonly DatabaseFixture _fixture;
          
          public OrderTests()
          {
              _fixture = new DatabaseFixture();
          }
          
          [Test]
          public async Task ProcessOrder_ValidOrder_Succeeds()
          {
              await _fixture.InitializeAsync();
              try
              {
                  // Test implementation
              }
              finally
              {
                  await _fixture.DisposeAsync();
              }
          }
      }
      ```

Test Methods:
  - Use [Test] attribute instead of [Fact]:
      ```csharp
      public class DiscountCalculatorTests
      {
          [Test]
          [Arguments(100m, 1, 0m)]      // No discount for single item
          [Arguments(100m, 5, 5m)]       // 5% for 5 items
          [Arguments(100m, 10, 10m)]     // 10% for 10 items
          public async Task CalculateDiscount_ReturnsCorrectAmount(
              decimal price,
              int quantity,
              decimal expectedDiscount)
          {
              // Arrange
              var calculator = new DiscountCalculator();
              
              // Act
              var discount = calculator.Calculate(price, quantity);
              
              // Assert
              await Assert.That(discount).IsEqualTo(expectedDiscount);
          }
      }
      ```
  - Follow Arrange-Act-Assert pattern:
      ```csharp
      [Test]
      public async Task ProcessOrder_ValidOrder_UpdatesInventory()
      {
          // Arrange
          var order = new Order(
              OrderId.New(),
              new[] { new OrderLine("SKU123", 5) });
          var repositoryFake = A.Fake<IRepository>();
          var processor = new OrderProcessor(repositoryFake);
          
          // Act
          var result = await processor.ProcessAsync(order);
          
          // Assert
          await Assert.That(result.IsSuccess).IsTrue();
          A.CallTo(() => repositoryFake.UpdateInventoryAsync(
                  A<string>._,
                  A<int>._))
              .MustHaveHappenedOnceExactly();
      }
      ```

Test Isolation:
  - Use fresh data for each test:
      ```csharp
      public class OrderTests
      {
          private static Order CreateTestOrder() =>
              new(OrderId.New(), TestData.CreateOrderLines());
              
          [Test]
          public async Task ProcessOrder_Success()
          {
              var order = CreateTestOrder();
              // Test implementation
          }
      }
      ```
  - Clean up resources:
      ```csharp
      public class IntegrationTests : IAsyncDisposable
      {
          private readonly TestServer _server;
          private readonly HttpClient _client;
          
          public IntegrationTests()
          {
              _server = new TestServer(CreateHostBuilder());
              _client = _server.CreateClient();
          }
          
          public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
          {
              _client.Dispose();
              await _server.DisposeAsync();
          }
      }
      ```

CI/CD Configuration:
  - Configure test runs with TUnit:
      ```yaml
      - name: Test
        run: |
          dotnet run --configuration Release --coverage --report-trx
      ```
    - TUnit includes built-in code coverage (via `--coverage` flag) and TRX report generation (via `--report-trx` flag)
    - No need for separate coverlet packages or Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk

Integration Testing:
  - Always use TestContainers for infrastructure:
      ```csharp
      // Good: Using TestContainers for database testing
      public class DatabaseTests : IAsyncLifetime
      {
          private readonly TestcontainersContainer _dbContainer;
          
          public DatabaseTests()
          {
              _dbContainer = new TestcontainersBuilder<TestcontainersContainer>()
                  .WithImage("mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest")
                  .WithEnvironment("ACCEPT_EULA", "Y")
                  .WithEnvironment("SA_PASSWORD", "Your_password123")
                  .WithPortBinding(1433, true)
                  .Build();
          }
          
          public async Task InitializeAsync()
          {
              await _dbContainer.StartAsync();
          }
          
          public async Task DisposeAsync()
          {
              await _dbContainer.DisposeAsync();
          }
      }
      
      // Good: Using TestContainers for Redis testing
      public class CacheTests : IAsyncLifetime
      {
          private readonly TestcontainersContainer _redisContainer;
          private IConnectionMultiplexer _redis;
          
          public CacheTests()
          {
              _redisContainer = new TestcontainersBuilder<TestcontainersContainer>()
                  .WithImage("redis:alpine")
                  .WithPortBinding(6379, true)
                  .Build();
          }
          
          public async Task InitializeAsync()
          {
              await _redisContainer.StartAsync();
              _redis = await ConnectionMultiplexer.ConnectAsync(
                  $"localhost:{_redisContainer.GetMappedPublicPort(6379)}");
          }
          
          public async Task DisposeAsync()
          {
              if (_redis is not null)
                  await _redis.DisposeAsync();
              await _redisContainer.DisposeAsync();
          }
      }
      
      // Good: Using TestContainers for message queue testing
      public class MessageQueueTests : IAsyncLifetime
      {
          private readonly TestcontainersContainer _rabbitContainer;
          private IConnection _connection;
          
          public MessageQueueTests()
          {
              _rabbitContainer = new TestcontainersBuilder<TestcontainersContainer>()
                  .WithImage("rabbitmq:management-alpine")
                  .WithPortBinding(5672, true)
                  .WithPortBinding(15672, true)
                  .Build();
          }
          
          public async Task InitializeAsync()
          {
              await _rabbitContainer.StartAsync();
              var factory = new ConnectionFactory
              {
                  HostName = "localhost",
                  Port = _rabbitContainer.GetMappedPublicPort(5672)
              };
              _connection = await factory.CreateConnectionAsync();
          }
          
          public async Task DisposeAsync()
          {
              await _connection.CloseAsync();
              await _rabbitContainer.DisposeAsync();
          }
      }
      ```
      
  - Avoid mocking infrastructure:
      ```csharp
      // Avoid: Mocking database
      public class DatabaseTests
      {
          private readonly IDbConnection _fakeDb = A.Fake<IDbConnection>();
          
          [Test]
          public async Task Test_WithMockedDb()
          {
              A.CallTo(() => _fakeDb.QueryAsync<Order>())
                  .Returns(new[] { new Order() });
              // Test with mocked database - can miss real database behavior
          }
      }
      
      // Good: Real database in container
      public class DatabaseTests
      {
          private readonly TestcontainersContainer _dbContainer;
          private IDbConnection _db;
          
          public DatabaseTests()
          {
              _dbContainer = new TestcontainersBuilder<TestcontainersContainer>()
                  .WithImage("mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest")
                  .Build();
          }
          
          [Test]
          public async Task Test_WithRealDb()
          {
              await _dbContainer.StartAsync();
              try
              {
                  _db = new SqlConnection("connection-string");
                  await _db.OpenAsync();
                  
                  // Test with real database in container
                  var order = await _db.QuerySingleAsync<Order>(
                      "SELECT * FROM Orders WHERE Id = @Id",
                      new { Id = 1 });
              }
              finally
              {
                  await _db.DisposeAsync();
                  await _dbContainer.DisposeAsync();
              }
          }
      }
      ```
      
  - Use container networks for multi-container scenarios:
      ```csharp
      public class IntegrationTests : IAsyncLifetime
      {
          private readonly INetwork _network;
          private readonly TestcontainersContainer _dbContainer;
          private readonly TestcontainersContainer _redisContainer;
          
          public IntegrationTests()
          {
              _network = new TestcontainersNetwork();
              
              _dbContainer = new TestcontainersBuilder<TestcontainersContainer>()
                  .WithImage("postgres:latest")
                  .WithNetwork(_network)
                  .WithNetworkAliases("db")
                  .Build();
                  
              _redisContainer = new TestcontainersBuilder<TestcontainersContainer>()
                  .WithImage("redis:alpine")
                  .WithNetwork(_network)
                  .WithNetworkAliases("redis")
                  .Build();
          }
          
          public async Task InitializeAsync()
          {
              await _network.CreateAsync();
              await Task.WhenAll(
                  _dbContainer.StartAsync(),
                  _redisContainer.StartAsync());
          }
          
          public async Task DisposeAsync()
          {
              await Task.WhenAll(
                  _dbContainer.DisposeAsync().AsTask(),
                  _redisContainer.DisposeAsync().AsTask());
              await _network.DisposeAsync();
          }
      }
      ```

Best Practices:
  - Name tests clearly:
      ```csharp
      // Good: Clear test names
      [Test]
      public async Task ProcessOrder_WhenInventoryAvailable_UpdatesStockAndReturnsSuccess()
      
      // Avoid: Unclear names
      [Test]
      public async Task TestProcessOrder()
      ```
  - Use meaningful assertions with TUnit:
      ```csharp
      // Good: Clear assertions
      await Assert.That(actual).IsEqualTo(expected);
      await Assert.That(collection).Contains(expectedItem);
      await Assert.That(() => processor.Process(invalidOrder))
          .Throws<OrderException>();
      
      // Avoid: Multiple assertions without context
      await Assert.That(result).IsNotNull();
      await Assert.That(result.Success).IsTrue();
      await Assert.That(result.Errors.Count).IsEqualTo(0);
      ```
  - Handle async operations properly:
      ```csharp
      // Good: Async test method
      [Test]
      public async Task ProcessOrder_ValidOrder_Succeeds()
      {
          await using var processor = new OrderProcessor();
          var result = await processor.ProcessAsync(order);
          await Assert.That(result.IsSuccess).IsTrue();
      }
      
      // Avoid: Sync over async
      [Test]
      public void ProcessOrder_ValidOrder_Succeeds()
      {
          using var processor = new OrderProcessor();
          var result = processor.ProcessAsync(order).Result;  // Can deadlock
          // TUnit assertions are async, so this won't compile
      }
      ```

Assertions:
  - Use TUnit's built-in assertions:
      ```csharp
      // Good: Using TUnit's built-in assertions
      public class OrderTests
      {
          [Test]
          public async Task CalculateTotal_WithValidLines_ReturnsCorrectSum()
          {
              // Arrange
              var order = new Order(
                  OrderId.New(),
                  new[]
                  {
                      new OrderLine("SKU1", 2, 10.0m),
                      new OrderLine("SKU2", 1, 20.0m)
                  });
              
              // Act
              var total = order.CalculateTotal();
              
              // Assert
              await Assert.That(total).IsEqualTo(40.0m);
          }
          
          [Test]
          public async Task Order_WithInvalidLines_ThrowsException()
          {
              // Arrange
              var invalidLines = new OrderLine[] { };
              
              // Act & Assert
              await Assert.That(() => new Order(OrderId.New(), invalidLines))
                  .Throws<ArgumentException>()
                  .WithMessageContaining("Order must have at least one line");
          }
          
          [Test]
          public async Task Order_WithValidData_HasExpectedProperties()
          {
              // Arrange
              var id = OrderId.New();
              var lines = new[] { new OrderLine("SKU1", 1, 10.0m) };
              
              // Act
              var order = new Order(id, lines);
              
              // Assert
              await Assert.That(order).IsNotNull();
              await Assert.That(order.Id).IsEqualTo(id);
              await Assert.That(order.Lines.Count).IsEqualTo(1);
              await Assert.That(order.Lines[0].Sku).IsEqualTo("SKU1");
              await Assert.That(order.Lines[0].Quantity).IsEqualTo(1);
              await Assert.That(order.Lines[0].Price).IsEqualTo(10.0m);
          }
      }
      ```
      
  - TUnit provides a modern, fluent assertion API that is built-in and doesn't require third-party libraries.
      
  - Use proper assertion types with TUnit:
      ```csharp
      public class CustomerTests
      {
          [Test]
          public async Task Customer_WithValidEmail_IsCreated()
          {
              // Boolean assertions
              await Assert.That(customer.IsActive).IsTrue();
              await Assert.That(customer.IsDeleted).IsFalse();
              
              // Equality assertions
              await Assert.That(customer.Email).IsEqualTo("john@example.com");
              await Assert.That(customer.Id).IsNotEqualTo(Guid.Empty);
              
              // Collection assertions
              await Assert.That(customer.Orders).IsEmpty();
              await Assert.That(customer.Roles).Contains("Admin");
              await Assert.That(customer.Roles).DoesNotContain("Guest");
              
              // Type assertions
              await Assert.That(customer).IsInstanceOf<PremiumCustomer>();
              await Assert.That(customer).IsAssignableTo<ICustomer>();
              
              // String assertions
              await Assert.That(customer.Reference).StartsWith("CUST");
              await Assert.That(customer.Description).Contains("Premium");
              
              // Range assertions
              await Assert.That(customer.Age).IsGreaterThanOrEqualTo(18);
              await Assert.That(customer.Age).IsLessThanOrEqualTo(100);
              
              // Reference assertions
              await Assert.That(actualCustomer).IsSameAs(expectedCustomer);
              await Assert.That(actualCustomer).IsNotSameAs(differentCustomer);
          }
      }
      ```
      
  - Use TUnit assertions for complex collections:
      ```csharp
      [Test]
      public async Task ProcessOrder_CreatesExpectedEvents()
      {
          // Arrange
          var processor = new OrderProcessor();
          var order = CreateTestOrder();
          
          // Act
          var events = processor.Process(order);
          
          // Assert
          await Assert.That(events.Count).IsEqualTo(3);
          await Assert.That(events[0]).IsInstanceOf<OrderReceivedEvent>();
          var received = (OrderReceivedEvent)events[0];
          await Assert.That(received.OrderId).IsEqualTo(order.Id);
          
          await Assert.That(events[1]).IsInstanceOf<InventoryReservedEvent>();
          var reserved = (InventoryReservedEvent)events[1];
          await Assert.That(reserved.OrderId).IsEqualTo(order.Id);
          await Assert.That(reserved.ReservedItems).IsNotEmpty();
          
          await Assert.That(events[2]).IsInstanceOf<OrderConfirmedEvent>();
          var confirmed = (OrderConfirmedEvent)events[2];
          await Assert.That(confirmed.OrderId).IsEqualTo(order.Id);
          await Assert.That(confirmed.IsSuccess).IsTrue();
      }
      ```

Mocking with FakeItEasy:
  - Use FakeItEasy for creating fakes (mocks):
      ```csharp
      using FakeItEasy;
      
      public class OrderProcessorTests
      {
          [Test]
          public async Task ProcessOrder_ValidOrder_CallsRepository()
          {
              // Arrange
              var repositoryFake = A.Fake<IRepository>();
              var processor = new OrderProcessor(repositoryFake);
              var order = new Order(OrderId.New(), TestData.CreateOrderLines());
              
              // Act
              await processor.ProcessAsync(order);
              
              // Assert
              A.CallTo(() => repositoryFake.SaveAsync(
                      A<Order>.That.Matches(o => o.Id == order.Id),
                      A<CancellationToken>._))
                  .MustHaveHappenedOnceExactly();
          }
      }
      ```
      
  - Configure fake behavior:
      ```csharp
      // Configure return values
      var repositoryFake = A.Fake<IRepository>();
      A.CallTo(() => repositoryFake.GetByIdAsync(A<Guid>._))
          .Returns(new Order { Id = testOrderId });
      
      // Configure to throw exceptions
      A.CallTo(() => repositoryFake.GetByIdAsync(A<Guid>._))
          .Throws<NotFoundException>();
      
      // Configure with argument constraints
      A.CallTo(() => repositoryFake.GetByIdAsync(
              A<Guid>.That.Matches(id => id != Guid.Empty)))
          .Returns(new Order());
      ```
      
  - Common argument constraints:
      ```csharp
      // Ignore arguments
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method(A<string>._)).Returns("result");
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method(A<string>.Ignored)).Returns("result");
      
      // Match exact values
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method("exact value")).Returns("result");
      
      // Match with predicate
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method(
              A<string>.That.Matches(s => s.Length > 5)))
          .Returns("result");
      
      // Match with That matchers
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method(
              A<string>.That.Contains("substring")))
          .Returns("result");
      ```
      
  - Verify calls:
      ```csharp
      // Verify call happened
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method(A<string>._)).MustHaveHappened();
      
      // Verify call happened exactly once
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method(A<string>._)).MustHaveHappenedOnceExactly();
      
      // Verify call never happened
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method(A<string>._)).MustNotHaveHappened();
      
      // Verify call happened specific number of times
      A.CallTo(() => fake.Method(A<string>._))
          .MustHaveHappened(3, Times.Exactly);
      ```
      
  - Configure properties:
      ```csharp
      var contextFake = A.Fake<ConsumeContext<Order>>();
      A.CallTo(() => contextFake.Message).Returns(orderMessage);
      
      // Or set property directly if it's writable
      contextFake.Message = orderMessage;
      ```

